10) Can you store different data types in an array?
-->In Java, the direct answer is no, you cannot store different data types in a standard array because Java arrays are homogeneous, 
    meaning they can only hold elements of a single, specified data type.

    However, there is a common workaround: 
      you can create an array of the Object class. Since Object is the root superclass for all classes in Java, an Object[] 
      array can store references to any object, effectively allowing you to mix different types.



11) Difference between shallow copy and deep copy of arrays
-->🔹 Shallow Copy
    int[] a = {1,2,3};
    int[] b = a;
    
    👉 Both refer to same array
    
    🔹 Deep Copy
    int[] a = {1,2,3};
    int[] b = a.clone();
    
    👉 Separate memory



12) How do you declare a 2D array?
-->int[][] arr;


13) How do you instantiate a 2D array?
-->int[][] arr = new int[3][3];


14) How to access elements in a 2D array?
-->Zero-Based Indexing: Both row and column indices start at 0. For example, the first element in the first row is at [0][0].
    Order: The first index specifies the row, and the second index specifies the column.
    Boundaries: Valid indices for an array of size \(N\) range from \(0\) to \(N - 1\). Accessing an index outside this range results in\
    an ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException.


15) Difference between rectangular and jagged arrays
-->The primary difference between rectangular and jagged arrays in Java is their structure: rectangular arrays have rows of equal length,
    while jagged arrays (also called ragged arrays) consist of rows that can have different lengths.
    🔹 Rectangular:
    int[][] arr = new int[3][3];
    
    👉 Equal columns
    
    🔹 Jagged:
    int[][] arr = new int[3][];
    arr[0] = new int[2];
    arr[1] = new int[3];
    
    👉 Different column sizes


16) How to declare and instantiate, & access 3D array?
-->In Java, a 3D array is an array of arrays of arrays. You can handle it in three main ways:
        1. Declaration and Instantiation
        You can declare a 3D array by using three sets of square brackets [][][].
        Fixed Size: Use the new keyword and specify all dimensions immediately.
        
        // Creates a 3x4x2 array (3 layers, 4 rows, 2 columns)
        int[][][] array = new int[3][4][2]; 
